.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">St Leonards and Hastings Rail Improvement Programme (SHRIMP)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The group also works in close partnership with West Sussex Rail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Users Association, Employers in Crawley and Brighton Line Commuters, East Sussex County Council, Eastbourne Borough Council, Rother District Council, Hastings Borough Council and the Local Chamber of Commerce across the area, representing over 50,000 rail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">users across the region. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Agenda Subject 1: Select Committee Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First up this week on our East Sussex Rail Alliance Agenda is the Evidence being sought by the Parliamentary Select Committee for Transport into the over-Christmas Gatwick Airport and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rail Services disruptions crisis. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">You maybe aware that Hastings and Bexhill which has a population of 140,000 combined when nearby rural areas are included was cut off for rail users for many days over Christmas. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On behalf of ESRA and its East Sussex rai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l travelling stakeholder groups (from Brighton through to Rye), we wish to draw the attention of the Committee to the major disparity between Rail Franchise holders for the South East region, in particular Southern who responded well to the emergencies and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> SouthEastern who failed to the point of complacency. www.eastsussexrail.org.uk 1 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> East Sussex Rail Alliance Putting Sussex back on the map </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Here is a recap of what occurred over the late December and Christmas period -</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">22nd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: The SouthEastern Tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in service from Hastings to London Charing Cross line became blocked to a landslip at Wadhurst </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">24th December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: Many services did not run but local bus operator Stagecoach Sussex ran their services across the county. Significantly however tickets were not t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ransferable from rail to bus as no reciprocal ticket arrangement had been set up. National Express also ran their two a day coach service to London. The Hastings line remained closed due to the landslip at Wadhurst. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">26th December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: We contacted rail operat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ors to advise on their plans, taking into account the warning weather forecast 27th December. Southern Trains suggested services would be running after safety checks had taken place. However Network Rail took the decision to close South Eastern Train netwo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rk services until midday on 27th December. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">27th December Operations - SouthEastern Trains - Hastings-London </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1. This train operator did not make had failed to organise bus replacements even though Southern trains had booked buses for the Hastings to Ashfo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rd service. This is a much less used service in contrast to the Hastings to London services. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2. This train operator did not make any effort to contact Stagecoach Sussex who did operate buses between Hastings and Tunbridge Wells on this day. Therefore dive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rted Rail Passengers travelling on their buses had to rebuy bus tickets. Then subsequently make Delay Repay Claims. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Significant Planning Factor 1:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It was the Southern Trains and South West Trains network that was most hit by the storms so it was something</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a surprise that Robin Gisby, Board Operations Director of Network Rail, closed the South Eastern Trains network until 1200, despite South Eastern Trains being the least affected. This was considered a huge misjudgment as many travellers and workers wer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e stranded in East Sussex and areas of Kent when many of their train lines were actually clear for safe running. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Significant Planning Factor 2: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Considering the Hastings line had been closed since 22nd December. SouthEastern Trains has failed to explain w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hy a fleet of buses had not been on standby as part of their Disaster Recovery Plan. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Communications failure 1: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">South Eastern trains were showing on realtimetrains.co.ukand nationalrail.co.uk that services were running between Ashford International and Lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndon St Pancras at 0700 despite Network Rail's decision to keep that part of the network closed until 1200. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Communications failure 2: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Twitter system and the resources working for South Eastern Train seemed unaware that there were trains running between Ashford International and London St Pancras until a passenger tweeted they were on board one of these trains. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Rail Service resumptio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first South Eastern train to leave Hastings for Charing Cross was at 1231 hours on 27th December after no services for 5 days. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ESRA experience of previous failures: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is not the first time South Eastern trains have been discovered not to have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a working Disaster Recovery Plan. On several occasions during snow periods the train service between Hastings and London has not been operational, even cut off for weeks at a time, without bus replacements over extended period, despite Stagecoach Sussex ru</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nning their buses. There appears no evidence of reciprocal arrangements between SouthEastern Trains and Stagecoach buses in East Sussex - in contrast to other areas such as Crawley with Metrobus and Brighton with the local bus firm and West Sussex with the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Stagecoach 700 Coastliner service. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ESRA conclusions: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are unclear as to how this operator can be permitted consistently not to provide a Disaster Recovery Plan. Because of this deficiency Hastings and other areas of East Sussex and Kent were without r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ail transportation for days and sometimes weeks. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While the train operator has an acclaimed performance on the High Speed services between Ashford International and London St Pancras, it appears that the whole performance of this train operator is aggregat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed as one. Therefore we would request that the performance over this franchise is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">retrospectively analysed to deliver the real time and on time performance for the Hastings to London via Tunbridge Wells line so we can understand the seriousness of the serv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ice provided. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> 27th December Operations - Southern trains - Ashford-Hastings-London </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This train operator could not run a train service between Ashford and Hastings very early morning, but had replacement buses in place. The rail service was able to recomm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence at 0700hours. This was also communicated through the Southern trains website, twitter and nationalrail.co.uk </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Southern Trains also started running from start of service from Hastings, Bexhill to Three Bridges where they had a fleet of buses to take cu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stomers to Coulsdon Town for connecting trains to London Victoria. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Wadhurst landslip evidence </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We note that Network Rail does not have emergency access to the railway track along the Hastings Line. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Item 1 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Charles Hendry MP </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">House of Commons </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Dear Mr. He</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndry </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Re: Hastings Line services </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I’m writing to ask a small favour. I did leave a message with your office,but appreciate that its the holiday season. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In brief, you will know that services have been disrupted on the Hastings Line since before Christmas as a result of a landslip near Wadhurst. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Network Rail has worked hard to clear this but work has been delayed due to adverse weather conditions </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ult, I’m afraid a five mile per hour emergency speed restriction applies on the “up” line for around 150 metres and a 20 mph emergency speed restriction applies on the “down” line. This is causing a time loss of up to seven minutes (more on longer trains).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> And on a busy network like ours, any delay of more than a few minutes can have a domino effect on other lines and services. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clearing the landslip requires extensive work but unfortunately, access to the site is being frustrated by the local land owner. N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etwork Rail is seeking legal powers to gain access, which unfortunately, takes time. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Via Network Rail, we can give contact details for the landowner, and if you would be willing to have a quiet word, to emphasise the importance of our being able to operat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e punctual services once commuters return to work from 6 January, this would be much appreciated. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If you need to discuss, please ask your office to give me a call. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I have copied this email to other Hastings line MPs whose constituents will also be affect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed by the landslip and to local rail user groups. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Yours sincerely </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mike Gibson </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Public Affairs Manager </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Southeastern </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ESRA - Proposed Questions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1/ South Eastern Train Operator and Network Rail should be asked to deliver specific on time statistics and real time statistics for the Hastings to London Charing Cross Line for the period of the current Franchise since inception. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2/ Network Rail should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be asked to explain their decision to close the South Eastern Network (and not South West or Southern Trains network) until 1200 on 27th December when the forecasts for weather highlighted that the storm pattern was more acute in Hampshire and West Sussex.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3/ Why did South Eastern Trains not provide any bus replacements on 27th December when other operators such as Southern, South West Trains, and Virgin Trains did. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4/ If South Eastern Trains and Network Rail knew that Wadhurst had a landslip why did they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not have a replacement service buses on standby when Southern were able to resource buses in the same area for a train services on the Hastings to Ashford line that carries less passengers than the Hastings to Tunbridge Wells. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Agenda SUBJECT 2: Failure t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">o uncover Real Time Performance </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ESRA is concerned that it appears that a smoke screen is being employed to prevent full transparency and therefore understanding of how punctuality of specific rail routes is accountable to the public. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We now provide evide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nce (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">item 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) by the ORR and Network Rail that suggests that a Freedom of Information request cannot be answered relating to the performance of the Hastings Lines. This appears to be hidden by Acts that overly prote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ct "</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sensitive" commercial data. This respo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nse is to the detriment of passengers using the Hastings line who over the last four years have suffered poor weather disruption,even though fares on this line have increased hugely to pay for the High Speed line from Ashford that provides these same passe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ngers no benefit. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore the neighbouring Wealden line in East Sussex which has an efficient performance operated by Southern Trains has commuter fares 30% cheaper for the equal distance from London. This Wealden line is suffering increasing overcrow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding due to passengers migrating from the poor performing Hastings Line. This is compounded by the journey time from Hastings to London is over 1 hour 45 minutes for a 66 mile journey, affected by infrastructure constraints. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Example Frant to London Bridge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">£106.50 (Hastings Line) per week versus Eridge to London Bridge £68.70 per week (Wealden Line)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – exact same distance from London yet same distance from London Bridge and less than five miles apart. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Item 2 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">REQUEST FOR INFORMATION REAL TIME DATA OUR REF Fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I 13-14/144 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Freedom of Information request of ORR/Network Rail </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Real time Performance statistics of Hastings-Tonbridge-London and Hastings via Brighton lines - 2013 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further to our request to understand the performance in financial and operating terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the franchise holders Southern and SouthEastern in particular, we make the further request to identify the performance over the past year on individual routes - specifically London-Tonbridge Hastings and London Victoria-Hastings (via London-Brighton Main L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ine) - as these are hidden in a blanket coverage of South East performance measures. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ESRA evidence suggests that service performance in parts of each franchise area are being used to cover a wide disparity in the averages quoted. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thank you for your respo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nse thus far. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Richard Tilden Smith </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On behalf of East Sussex Rail Alliance </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From: contact. Date: Thu, 5 Dec 2013 15:56:34 +0000 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Dear Mr Tilden Smith </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I write further to your e-mail of 7 th November, requesting real time data for the current Southern and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">South Eastern train franchises and details of compensation payments paid by Network Rail to these franchises. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am handling your request under the terms of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (FoIA 2000). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> From reading your request we suspect that you ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tually require “right time data”, which is the number of trains arriving early or within 59 seconds of the planned arrival time. Real time refers to the information provided through station display boards, websites and apps, which give passengers informati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on on when trains are due to arrive/depart at the station. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Right time data is published annually by ORR at a national level and by sector (London and South East, Long Distance and Regional), details can be found on our data portal at http://dataportal.orr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.gov.uk/displayreport/report/html/2deb842d-35a2-464f-a076-090d54f02a1c </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we do hold right time data at a Train Operator and sub-operator level, I am sorry but I am unable to release the data. This information has been supplied by Network Rail and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> train operating companies, obtained through our economic functions and considered to be exempt from disclosure under s.44 of FoIA 2000 – prohibitions on disclosure. The s.44 exemption is an absolute exemption and is by virtue of the prohibition on disclos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ure of such information set out in s.145 of the Railways Act 1993. In broad terms ORR cannot publish information about a business (e.g. Network Rail, a TOC etc) that has been obtained in the exercise of our functions as an economic regulator. Indeed it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a criminal offence if such information is disclosed. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Network Rail do however publish a right time moving annual average by individual train operator the end of each monthly operating period which can be found at http://www.networkrail.co.uk/about/performa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nce/. I would suggest that you contact Network Rail who may be able to supply you with more data for Southern and South Eastern: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mark Farrow </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Head of Transparency&amp; Business Ethics </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ORR does not hold information on compensation payments paid by Network Rail to train operators, and even if we did this information would be covered by the s.44 exemption. We would suggest contacting Network Rail for this information. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Should you ha